1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,640
So, we all have some behavior that we would like to change about ourselves.

2
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:25,760
And we certainly all want to help someone else change their behavior in a positive way.

3
00:00:25,760 --> 00:00:28,680
So maybe it's your kids, your spouse, your colleague.

4
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:34,360
So I want to share some new research with you that I think reveals something really important

5
00:00:34,360 --> 00:00:41,720
about what gets people to change their behavior. But before I do that, let's zoom in on one strategy

6
00:00:41,720 --> 00:00:47,080
that I think you probably use a lot. So let's say you're trying to stop yourself from snacking.

7
00:00:47,880 --> 00:00:52,520
What do you tell yourself? Well, most people's in a monologue will say,

8
00:00:52,520 --> 00:01:00,920
be where you'll be fat. And if this was your kid, you would probably tell him that

9
00:01:01,640 --> 00:01:08,280
smoking kills. And by the way, he's in big, big trouble. So what we're trying to do here

10
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:14,920
is we're trying to scare ourselves and others into changing their behavior. And it's not just us.

11
00:01:15,560 --> 00:01:20,440
Warnings and threats are really common in health campaigns, in policy.

12
00:01:21,400 --> 00:01:26,680
It's because we all share this deep rooted belief that if you threaten people,

13
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:33,560
if fear is induced, it will get them to act. And it seems like a really reasonable assumption,

14
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:41,320
except for the fact that the science shows that warnings have very limited impact on behavior.

15
00:01:42,360 --> 00:01:47,800
So graphic images on cigarette packets, for example, do not deter smokers from smoking.

16
00:01:47,880 --> 00:01:52,760
And one study found that after looking at those images, quitting actually became a lower priority

17
00:01:52,760 --> 00:01:57,400
for smokers. So I'm not saying that warnings and threats never work, but what I'm saying is that

18
00:01:57,400 --> 00:02:01,480
on average, they seem to have a very limited impact. And so the question is why?

19
00:02:02,600 --> 00:02:09,640
Why are we resistant to warnings? Well, if you think about animals, when you induce fear in an

20
00:02:09,640 --> 00:02:17,000
animal, the most common response you will see is freezing or fleeing, fighting not as much.

21
00:02:17,960 --> 00:02:23,720
And so humans are the same. So something scares us. We tend to shut down and we try to eliminate

22
00:02:23,720 --> 00:02:29,080
the negative feelings. So we might use rationalization. So for example, you might tell yourself,

23
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:33,640
my grandfather smoked, he lived to be 90. So I have really good genes and absolutely nothing to

24
00:02:33,640 --> 00:02:40,040
worry about. And this process can actually make you feel more resilient than you did before,

25
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:44,120
which is why warnings sometimes have this boomerang effect.

26
00:02:45,080 --> 00:02:51,560
And other times, we simply put our head in the ground. Take the stock market, for example.

27
00:02:51,560 --> 00:02:55,480
Do you know when people pull their head out of the ground to look at their account,

28
00:02:55,480 --> 00:03:01,000
not to make a transaction just to log in to check their account? So what you're seeing here in

29
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:08,360
black is the S&P 500 over two years. And in gray is a number of times that people logged into

30
00:03:08,360 --> 00:03:13,240
their account just to check. And this is data from calls and loans seen in SEPP. It's controlled

31
00:03:13,240 --> 00:03:19,080
for all the obvious content. So what do we see? So when the market is high, people log in all the

32
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:26,040
time because positive information makes you feel good. So you seek it out. And when the market is

33
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:32,120
low, people avoid logging in because negative information makes us feel bad. So we try to avoid

34
00:03:32,120 --> 00:03:40,440
it altogether. And all this is true as long as bad information can reasonably be avoided.

35
00:03:41,400 --> 00:03:46,760
So what you don't see here is what happened a few months later in the financial collapse of 2008

36
00:03:46,760 --> 00:03:51,320
when the market went drastically down. And that's when people started logging in frantically.

37
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:57,400
But it was a bit too late. So you can think about it like this. It's not just finance.

38
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:05,960
In many different parts of our life, we have warning signs and bad behaviors now.

39
00:04:06,920 --> 00:04:13,720
And they could potentially lead to all these bad outcomes later. But not necessarily so.

40
00:04:14,360 --> 00:04:18,760
Because there's different routes from your present to your future, right? It can go this way,

41
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:25,080
it can go that way. And as time passes, you gather more and more information about where the wind

42
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:32,840
is blowing. And at any point, you can intervene. And you could potentially change the outcome.

43
00:04:33,720 --> 00:04:37,480
But that takes energy. And you might tell yourself, well, what's a point about worrying about

44
00:04:37,480 --> 00:04:44,520
something that might happen? It might not happen. Until we reach this point, at which time you do

45
00:04:44,520 --> 00:04:50,840
jump into action, but sometimes it's a little bit too late. So we wanted to know in my lab,

46
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:56,520
what type of information does leak into people? So we conducted an experiment where we asked

47
00:04:56,520 --> 00:05:02,600
approximately 100 people to estimate the likelihood of 80 different negative events that might

48
00:05:02,600 --> 00:05:08,680
happen to them in the future. So for example, I might ask you, what is a likelihood that you will

49
00:05:08,680 --> 00:05:16,200
suffer hearing loss in your future? And let's say you think, it's about 50%. Then I give you

50
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:22,600
the opinion of two different experts. So expert A tells you, you know, for someone like you,

51
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:30,120
I think it's only 40%. So they give you a rosier view of your future. Expert B says,

52
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:36,760
you know, for someone like you, I actually think it's about 60%. It's worse. So they give you

53
00:05:36,760 --> 00:05:44,280
a bleaker view of your future. What should you do? Well, you shouldn't change your beliefs, right?

54
00:05:45,720 --> 00:05:51,400
Wrong. What we find is that people tend to change their beliefs towards a more desirable opinion.

55
00:05:53,240 --> 00:06:00,840
In other words, people listen to the positive information. Now, this study was conducted on

56
00:06:00,840 --> 00:06:05,960
college students. So you might say, well, college students are delusional, right? We all know that.

57
00:06:06,920 --> 00:06:12,360
And surely as we grow older, we grow wiser. So we said, okay, let's test that. Does this really

58
00:06:12,360 --> 00:06:16,200
generalize? Does it generalize to your kid? Does it generalize to your parent? Does it generalize

59
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:21,080
to your spouse? And so we tested people from the age of 10 until the age of 80.

60
00:06:22,040 --> 00:06:28,520
And the answer was yes. In all these age groups, people take an information they want to hear,

61
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:33,160
like someone telling you, you're more attractive than you thought than information that they don't

62
00:06:33,160 --> 00:06:40,280
want to hear. And the ability to learn from good news, it remained quite stable throughout the lifespan.

63
00:06:41,800 --> 00:06:48,840
But the ability to learn from bad news, that changes as you age. So what we found was that

64
00:06:48,920 --> 00:06:54,680
kids and teenagers, they were the worst at learning from bad news. And the ability became better

65
00:06:54,680 --> 00:07:02,360
and better as people aged. But then around the age of 40, around midlife, it started deteriorating

66
00:07:02,360 --> 00:07:09,960
again. So what this means is that the most vulnerable populations, kids and teenagers on the one hand

67
00:07:09,960 --> 00:07:14,920
and the elderly on the other hand, they're the least likely to accurately learn from warnings.

68
00:07:15,880 --> 00:07:22,360
But what you can see here is that it doesn't matter what age you are, you can be 20, 30, 40, 50 or 60.

69
00:07:22,920 --> 00:07:27,000
Everyone takes an information they want to hear more than information that they don't.

70
00:07:28,360 --> 00:07:31,160
And so we end up with a view like this of ourselves.

71
00:07:31,400 --> 00:07:48,120
And our mistake as teachers, as mentors, as employers, is that instead of working with this positive

72
00:07:48,120 --> 00:07:53,800
image that people so effortfully maintain, we try and put a clear mirror in front of them.

73
00:07:54,840 --> 00:07:59,320
We tell them, you know, the image is just going to get worse and worse and worse and it doesn't work.

74
00:08:00,280 --> 00:08:07,000
It doesn't work because the brain will frantically try to distort the image using Photoshop and fancy

75
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:15,400
lenses until it gets the image is happy with. But what will happen if we went along with how our

76
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:22,680
brain works and not against it? Take handwashing, for example. So we all know that handwashing

77
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:27,000
is a number one way to prevent the spread of disease. And this is really important in hospitals.

78
00:08:27,720 --> 00:08:33,640
So in a hospital here in the United States, a camera was installed to see how often medical staff

79
00:08:33,640 --> 00:08:40,840
do in fact sanitize their hands before and after entering a patient's room. Now, the medical staff,

80
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:49,000
they knew a camera was installed. Nevertheless, only one in ten washed their hands before and after

81
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:56,200
entering a patient's room. But then an intervention was introduced. An electronic board

82
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:02,120
that told the medical staff how well they were doing. Every time you wash your hands,

83
00:09:02,120 --> 00:09:07,800
the numbers went on and this is up on the screen. And it showed you your rate of your current shift

84
00:09:07,800 --> 00:09:19,000
and the rate of the weekly staff. And what happened? Boom. Compliance raised to 90%, which is absolutely

85
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:24,920
amazing. And the research staff were amazed as well and they made sure to replicate it in another

86
00:09:24,920 --> 00:09:33,240
division in the hospital again, the same results. So why does this intervention work so well?

87
00:09:35,400 --> 00:09:42,280
It works well because instead of using warnings about bad things that can happen in the future

88
00:09:42,280 --> 00:09:49,960
like disease, it uses free principles that we know really drive your mind and your behavior.

89
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:59,320
Let me explain. So the first one is social incentives. In the hospital study, the medical staff

90
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:03,720
could see what other people are doing, right? They can see the rate of the shift, the rate of the

91
00:10:03,720 --> 00:10:09,800
week. We're social people. We really care what other people are doing. We want to do the same and

92
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:15,560
we want to do it better. This is an image from a study that we conducted led by PhD student,

93
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:22,280
Micah Adelson, and what it's showing you, it's a signal in the emotional center of your brain

94
00:10:22,280 --> 00:10:28,440
when you hear about the opinion of others. And what we found was that this signal can predict

95
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:33,720
how likely you are to conform at a later time. How likely you are to change your behavior.

96
00:10:35,560 --> 00:10:42,120
So the British government are using this principle to get people to pay taxes on time.

97
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:49,240
In an old letter that they sent to people who forgot to pay taxes on time, they simply stressed

98
00:10:49,240 --> 00:10:54,520
how important it was to pay taxes and that didn't help. So then they added one sentence.

99
00:10:55,720 --> 00:11:01,320
And that sentence said, 9 out of 10 people in Britain pay their taxes on time.

100
00:11:02,360 --> 00:11:07,320
And that one sentence enhanced compliance within that group by 15%.

101
00:11:08,280 --> 00:11:14,840
And it's fought to bring into the British government 5.6 billion pounds. So highlighting what

102
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:21,240
other people are doing is a really strong incentive. The other principle is immediate rewards.

103
00:11:23,080 --> 00:11:29,160
So every time the staff wash their hand, they could see the numbers go up in the board and it made

104
00:11:29,160 --> 00:11:35,320
them feel good. And knowing that in advance, made them do something that they otherwise may not want

105
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:42,600
to do. Now, this works because we value immediate rewards. Reports that we can get now

106
00:11:43,320 --> 00:11:49,480
more than rewards that we can get in the future. And people tend to think it's because we don't

107
00:11:49,480 --> 00:11:53,480
care about the future, but that's completely wrong. I mean, we all care about our future, right?

108
00:11:53,480 --> 00:11:57,000
We want to be happy, we want to be healthy in the future, we want to be successful.

109
00:11:57,880 --> 00:12:03,560
But the future is so far away. I mean, maybe you'll be happy badly now and you'll be fine in the

110
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:12,840
future. And maybe you'll be all together dead. So the here and now you would rather have that

111
00:12:12,840 --> 00:12:18,200
tangible drink, that tangible tea bone rather than something that's uncertain in the future.

112
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:23,960
If you think about it, it's not altogether irrational, right? You're choosing something sure now

113
00:12:23,960 --> 00:12:31,480
rather than something that's unsure in the future. But what will happen if you reward people now

114
00:12:32,200 --> 00:12:39,800
for doing actions that are good for them in the future? So studies show that giving people

115
00:12:39,800 --> 00:12:45,320
immediate rewards makes them more likely to quit smoking, more likely to start exercising,

116
00:12:45,320 --> 00:12:51,640
and this effect lasts for at least six months. Because not smoking becomes associated with a reward.

117
00:12:52,280 --> 00:12:58,280
And exercising becomes associated with a reward, and it becomes a habit. It becomes a lifestyle.

118
00:12:58,680 --> 00:13:03,720
So we can reward ourselves and others now for behaving in ways that are good for us in the future,

119
00:13:03,720 --> 00:13:09,880
and that's a way for us to bridge the temporal gap. And the first principle is progress monitoring.

120
00:13:11,160 --> 00:13:15,960
So the electronic boards focus the medical staff attention on improving their performance.

121
00:13:17,080 --> 00:13:21,480
This is an image from a study that we conducted that shows you brain activity

122
00:13:21,480 --> 00:13:25,880
suggestive of efficient coding of positive information about the future.

123
00:13:26,440 --> 00:13:33,320
And what we found was that the brain does a really good job at this, but it doesn't do such a good

124
00:13:33,320 --> 00:13:40,520
job at processing negative information about the future. So what does this mean? It means that if

125
00:13:40,520 --> 00:13:45,960
you're trying to get people's attention, you might want to highlight the progress, not the decline.

126
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:52,520
So for example, if you take that kid with a cigarette, you might want to tell them,

127
00:13:53,240 --> 00:13:59,160
you know, if you stop smoking, you'll become better at sports. Highlight the progress, not the decline.

128
00:13:59,960 --> 00:14:05,400
Now before I sum up, let me just share this small anecdote with you. So a few weeks ago,

129
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:10,280
I got home and I found this bill on my fridge. And I was really surprised because there's

130
00:14:10,280 --> 00:14:14,520
never any bills on my fridge. So I was wondering why my husband decided to put that on our fridge.

131
00:14:15,480 --> 00:14:20,680
And so looking at the bill, I could see that what this bill was trying to do is get me to be

132
00:14:20,680 --> 00:14:26,680
more efficient with my electricity use. And how was it doing it? Social incentives,

133
00:14:26,680 --> 00:14:31,560
immediate rewards, and progress monitoring. Let me show you. So here's a social incentives.

134
00:14:32,200 --> 00:14:37,320
So in gray is the energy use on the average energy use of people in my neighborhood.

135
00:14:38,200 --> 00:14:43,320
And in blue is my energy use. And in green is a most efficient neighbor.

136
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:49,800
And my reaction to this was my immediate reaction was, I'm a little bit better than average.

137
00:14:50,680 --> 00:14:57,240
Tiny bit, but still, and my husband was the same exact same reaction. And I want to get to

138
00:14:57,240 --> 00:15:03,400
the green bar. And then I got a smiley face. That was my immediate reward. And it was telling me

139
00:15:03,400 --> 00:15:11,800
you're doing good. And it made me want to put this on my fridge. And also I have this one smiley

140
00:15:11,800 --> 00:15:15,000
face. I can see there's an opportunity there to get to smiley faces.

141
00:15:15,720 --> 00:15:23,080
So there's an opportunity for progress. And it's showing me my progress throughout the year,

142
00:15:23,080 --> 00:15:28,920
how my energy use changes throughout the year. And the last thing this bill gave me, it gave me

143
00:15:28,920 --> 00:15:35,960
a sense of control. So it gave me a sense that I was in control of my use of electricity.

144
00:15:35,960 --> 00:15:39,560
And that is a really important thing if you're trying to get people to change their behavior,

145
00:15:39,560 --> 00:15:44,200
because the brain is constantly trying to seek ways to control its environment. It's the one

146
00:15:44,200 --> 00:15:50,120
of the principles of what the brain is actually doing. And so giving people a sense of control

147
00:15:50,120 --> 00:15:58,200
is a really important motivator. Okay, so what am I not saying? I'm not saying that we do not

148
00:15:58,200 --> 00:16:05,640
need to communicate risks. And I'm not saying that there's one solution fits all. But I am saying

149
00:16:05,640 --> 00:16:13,560
that if we want to motivate change, we might want to rethink how we do it. Because fear,

150
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:19,320
the fear of losing your health, the fear of losing money, induces inaction. While the

151
00:16:19,320 --> 00:16:25,960
thrill of a gain induces action. And so to change behavior in ourselves and in others,

152
00:16:25,960 --> 00:16:32,920
we may want to try these positive strategies rather than threats, which really capitalize on the

153
00:16:32,920 --> 00:16:42,920
human tendency to seek progress. Thank you.

